    "title": "French (language): What is the difference between 'car' and 'parce que'? - Quora",
    "tags": [
        "Culture of France"
    ],
    "response": [
        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "Kevin Morice",
                "href": "/profile/Kevin-Morice"
            },
            "answer_text": "Parce que gives cause (\"because\")Car gives justification (\"since\", \"for\") In this \"parce que\" is a touch stronger. There are a few cases where the two are not interchangeable :- Anselme est malade, car je ne l'ai pas vu de la semaine- Anselme est malade, parce que je ne l'ai pas vu de la semaine(the second sentence sounds very wrong) Also, negative sentences tend to need car in order to reduce ambiguity:- Plectrude n'a pas \u00e9t\u00e9 choisie car son cousin \u00e9tait dans le jury- Plectrude n'a pas \u00e9t\u00e9 choisie parce que son cousin \u00e9tait dans le jury(in the second sentence, you don't know whether she was selected or not, only voice inflexion could clarify this) These examples are a little contrived but you'd be surprised at how often \"parce que\" (universally used in spoken French) leads to ambiguity.Solution : use car! You'll sound well-learned, and the only downside I see is that you cannot begin a sentence with it (unlike \"parce que\").Hope this helps. ",
